de.uka.ipd.sdq.beagle.core.evaluableexpressions.util

Class ModifyingEvaluableExpressionVisitor

  • java.lang.Object
    • de.uka.ipd.sdq.beagle.core.evaluableexpressions.util.ExpressionTreeWalker
      • de.uka.ipd.sdq.beagle.core.evaluableexpressions.util.PartialExpressionTreeWalker
        • de.uka.ipd.sdq.beagle.core.evaluableexpressions.util.ModifyingEvaluableExpressionVisitor

  • public abstract class ModifyingEvaluableExpressionVisitor
extends PartialExpressionTreeWalker
    A visitor allowing to create a new EvaluableExpression out of an existing one. Evaluable Expressions are immutable and can thus not simply be modified. However, it may often be wished to create a new expression out of an existing one that only differs from the initial one in some details.

    This visitor follows the same traversal strategy as RecursiveEvaluableExpressionVisitor. This means it will perform a depth-first traversal on the tree formed by the expression passed to modifyRecursively(de.uka.ipd.sdq.beagle.core.evaluableexpressions.EvaluableExpression). Implementors may call replaceCurrentExpressionWith(EvaluableExpression) in any hook. This will replace the currently visited expression and continue traversal in the replacement. Replacing an expression will lead to a replacement of all expressions that have the replaced expression as an inner expression. These “parent” expressions will be replaced by a new expression of the same type containing the same inner expressions except for the ones that were initially replaced.

    This visitor will start at the expression passed to modifyRecursively(EvaluableExpression) and call the according at hook. Afterwards, it will recursively visit all inner expressions and then call the after hook. Given that no expression is thrown, the traversal of one expression tree that only contains pairwise different inner expressions has these properties:

    • the number of all called at hooks will equal the number of all called after hooks. However, the numbers may differ for a type of specific hooks because the expression was changed during the visit. For example atSubstraction may be called on an expression that is replaced by an AdditionExpression in this hook. Thus afterAddition will be called instead of afterSubstraction at this position when traversing upwards.
    • if for two expression e1 and e2, atExpression(e1) was called before atExpression(e2) was, afterExpression(e2) will be called before afterExpression(e1) will be called.

    Please note that evaluable expressions may often contain an instance of one evaluable expression multiple times. Replacements do however only apply to the current position in the traversal tree (and not all occurences of the currently visited expression). For every new visit, traversing of inner expressions will be enabled.

    This visitor is not thread safe. It may only be used to traverse one expression at a time, meaning that its results are undefined if modifyRecursively(EvaluableExpression) is called when getTraversalDepth() does not return -1. There is however no limitation on how many expression trees can be visited by an instance of this class.

        Starts visiting expression.
        Parameters:
        expression - The expression forming the root of the expression tree that shall be traversed. Must not be null.
        Returns:
        The modified expression. This is the expression that was build to reflect all replacements. Will be expression if no substantial call to replaceCurrentExpressionWith(EvaluableExpression) was made.

      • replaceCurrentExpressionWith

        protected void replaceCurrentExpressionWith(EvaluableExpression expression)
        Replaces the currently visited expression with expression in the expression tree. This will lead the traversal to continue in expression and all expressions for which no after hooks have been called yet to be replaced by an expression reflecting this replacement. A call to this method has no effect if expression equals the momentarily visited expression.
        Parameters:
        expression - The new expression to be inserted at the point in the expression tree at which the current expression is found. Must not be null.
        Throws:
        IllegalStateException - If this visitor is currently not visiting an expression tree.
